er;'><em>&fnof;</em>(<em>&#981;</em>&middot;<em>&mu;</em>) = <em>k</em>&middot;<em>m</em> = <em>&fnof;</em>(<em>&#981;</em>)&middot;<em>&fnof;</em>(<em>&mu;</em>).</p>\nFinally, an element in the kernel of this homomorphism sends <em>&omega;<sub>n</sub></em> to <em>&omega;<sub>n</sub></em>, so Ker(<em>&fnof;</em>) is just the \nidentity element of Gal<sub>&#8474;</sub>(<em>K</em>).  Thus, <em>&fnof;</em> is an isomorphism \nfrom Gal<sub>&#8474;</sub>(<em>K</em>) to <em>Z<sub>n</sub></em><sup>&ast;</sup>.  Since we know that both Gal<sub>&#8474;</sub>(<em>K</em>) \nand <em>Z<sub>n</sub></em><sup>&ast;</sup> have <em>&#981;</em>(<em>n</em>) elements, the mapping is onto, \nso Gal<sub>&#8474;</sub>(<em>K</em>) &asymp; <em>Z<sub>n</sub></em><sup>&ast;</sup>.<br><br>\n\n<a href=\"#prop156ret\">Return to text</a>","pos":225,"type":"cell"}
